|~ ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
   qlang LSP showcase — open this file in VS Code with the
   qlang extension active to exercise every LSP feature.

   How to use:
     1. Ctrl+Click (Go to Definition) on any identifier
     2. Hover over operands, projections, keywords
     3. Ctrl+Shift+O (Outline) to see all bindings
     4. Shift+F12 (Find References) on any identifier
     5. Type inside parens for Signature Help
     6. Ctrl+Space for Completion anywhere
   ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ ~|


|~ ── 1. Hover ─────────────────────────────────────────────
   Hover over each operand to see its category and docs
   from manifest.qlang. Try: count, filter, sort, union,
   reify, if, coalesce, sortWith, asc, desc. ~|

[1 2 3 4 5] | count

[10 25 3 47 8 31] | filter(gt(20)) | sort

{:name "alice" :age 30} | /name

|~| Hover over /name → "projection /name — extracts value from Map"
|~| Hover over :age  → "keyword :age"


|~ ── 2. Go to Definition ─────────────────────────────────
   Ctrl+Click on a user binding jumps to its let/as
   declaration. Ctrl+Click on a builtin (count, filter,
   add...) jumps to manifest.qlang. ~|

|~~| Doubles a number. ~~|
let(:double, mul(2))

|~~| Triples a number. ~~|
let(:triple, mul(3))

|~| Ctrl+Click on `double` below → jumps to the let above
[1 2 3] * double

|~| Ctrl+Click on `triple` below → jumps to the let above
[10 20] * triple

|~| Ctrl+Click on `count` below → jumps to manifest.qlang
[1 2 3] | count


|~ ── 3. Shadowing ─────────────────────────────────────────
   When an identifier is rebound, go-to-definition jumps
   to the LAST visible declaration, not the first. ~|

let(:x, 1)
|~| x here is 1
let(:x, 99)
|~| Ctrl+Click on x below → jumps to let(:x, 99), not let(:x, 1)
x


|~ ── 4. Fork isolation ───────────────────────────────────
   Bindings inside (parens), [vecs], {maps}, #{sets} are
   fork-isolated. Go-to-definition respects this — a
   binding declared inside a fork is invisible outside. ~|

(42 | as(:inner) | inner)
|~| Ctrl+Click on `inner` at the END of the line above works
|~| (cursor is inside the paren group where inner is visible).
|~| But inner is NOT visible in subsequent pipeline steps
|~| outside the parens.


|~ ── 5. Find References ──────────────────────────────────
   Shift+F12 on any identifier shows all occurrences:
   declaration sites (let/as) and use sites. ~|

let(:greet, prepend("hello "))
"world" | greet
"qlang" | greet
|~| Shift+F12 on `greet` → 3 occurrences (1 declaration + 2 uses)


|~ ── 6. Document Symbols (Outline) ───────────────────────
   Ctrl+Shift+O opens the Outline pane. Every let binding
   shows as Function, every as binding shows as Variable.
   Try it — you should see: double, triple, x, inner,
   greet, and the bindings below. ~|

let(:votingAge, filter(/age | gte(18)))

42 | as(:answer)


|~ ── 7. Signature Help ───────────────────────────────────
   Type inside parentheses of an operand call to see its
   signature. The active parameter highlights as you type
   commas. Try editing inside the parens below. ~|

[{:name "a" :age 25} {:name "b" :age 15}]
  | filter(/age | gte(18))
  * /name

|~| Place cursor inside filter( ) and type — signature appears
|~| Place cursor after a comma inside add( , ) — second param highlights

{:x 10 :y 3} | add(/x, /y)


|~ ── 8. Completion ────────────────────────────────────────
   Ctrl+Space at any point shows completions: 65 builtin
   operands with docs + any user-defined bindings visible
   at the cursor position. ~|

let(:myHelper, mul(10))
|~| Type Ctrl+Space here → myHelper appears alongside builtins
|~| Type "my" then Ctrl+Space → filtered to myHelper


|~ ── 9. Diagnostics ──────────────────────────────────────
   Syntax errors show as red squiggles in real time.
   Uncomment the line below (remove the |~| prefix and
   the space) to see a parse error: ~|

|~| [1 2 3


|~ ── 10. Comments ─────────────────────────────────────────
   All four comment forms get syntax highlighting:
     |~|        line plain (this one)
     |~ ... ~|  block plain (the section headers above)
     |~~|       line doc (attaches to next let/as)
     |~~ ~~|    block doc (multi-line, attaches to next let/as)
   Doc comments appear in the docs field of reify descriptors. ~|

|~~| Computes the absolute value via conditional. ~~|
let(:abs, if(lt(0), mul(-1)))

|~~ Surround a string with a prefix and suffix.
    Parametric conduit with two parameters. ~~|
let(:@surround, [:pfx, :sfx], prepend(pfx) | append(sfx))

|~| Ctrl+Click on @surround below → jumps to the let above
"world" | @surround("[", "]")


|~ ── 11. Effect markers ───────────────────────────────────
   @-prefixed identifiers are effectful host operands.
   The @ sigil gets distinct highlighting. ~|

|~| @surround above is @-prefixed (harmless over-approximation).
|~| In the JDT domain, @callers, @refs, @hierarchy carry real
|~| side effects (Eclipse SearchEngine calls).


|~ ── 12. Comparator composition ───────────────────────────
   sortWith + asc/desc/nullsFirst/nullsLast + firstNonZero
   compose declaratively. Hover each to see docs. ~|

[{:name "c" :age 30} {:name "a" :age 25} {:name "b" :age 25}]
  | sortWith([asc(/age), desc(/name)] | firstNonZero)
  * /name
